<subSubSection id="78879BECFFBFFF846DB082B9FE8E0A21" pageId="2" pageNumber="197" type="etymology">
<paragraph id="3022C867FFBFFF846DB082B9FE8E0A21" blockId="2.[151,1437,1093,1876]" pageId="2" pageNumber="197">
<emphasis id="02E91475FFBFFF846DB082B9FED40BB1" bold="true" box="[199,334,1706,1732]" pageId="2" pageNumber="197">Etymology.</emphasis>
In honor of Barão do Rio Branco, a Brazilian diplomat, lawyer, historian, geographer, journalist, politician, and professor. Due to his diplomatic efforts, he managed to peacefully resolve several territorial disputes, consolidating the borders of modern 
<collectingCountry id="488A88F7FFBFFF846F4582E1FDE00A79" box="[562,634,1778,1804]" name="Brazil" pageId="2" pageNumber="197">Brazil</collectingCountry>
. One of his accomplishments was the addition of the territory of 
<collectingRegion id="F2590685FFBFFF84683C82E1FF480A45" country="Brazil" name="Amapa" pageId="2" pageNumber="197">Amapá State</collectingRegion>
, which became a part of 
<collectingCountry id="488A88F7FFBFFF846C868305FDAF0A45" box="[497,565,1814,1840]" name="Brazil" pageId="2" pageNumber="197">Brazil</collectingCountry>
in 1900, after a diplomatic dispute with the government of 
<collectingCountry id="488A88F7FFBFFF8469978305FAAA0A45" box="[1248,1328,1814,1840]" name="France" pageId="2" pageNumber="197">France</collectingCountry>
. Name in apposition.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
